   <p><QUOTE rend=blockquote><CIT><QUOTE>When Lord Lovat was brought from   Scotland, to be tried in London, Hogarth, having previously known him, went to meet him at St. Albans, for the purpose of taking his portrait, and at the  <Q> White Hart</Q>  in that town, found the hoary peer under the hands of his barber. The old nobleman rose to salute him, according to the Scotch and French fashion, with so much eagerness, that he left a large portion of the lather from his beard on the face of his old friend. He is drawn in the attitude of enumerating by his fingers the rebel forces--such a general had so many men, &amp;c.</QUOTE><BIBL>-J. Ireland.</BIBL></CIT></QUOTE>
